1.2. What is this document about?

1.2.1. Presentation of the data processing methodology

In the context of the tits reproduction study of the PubPrivLands project, we undertook a complex data processing methodology that can be divided into five stages:

  1. Raw data acquisition and preparation - This initial stage consists of all raw data acquisition through fieldwork, GIS or remote-sensing-based data generation, and database extractions as well as their initial cleaning and formatting to produce raw datasets (e.g.Â tits reproduction observations, environmental variables). This stage is globally described in the Materials & Methods section of the manuscript, and is thoroughly detailed in the ppl_log.pdf document (French only, see Supplementary Materials).
  2. Clean dataset generation - This stage includes all basic cleaning, wrangling, computing and formatting required to obtain a clean exploitable dataset. This stage is documented in the R files of the {ppl.tits} package openly accessible at: https://github.com/mrelnoob/ppl.tits.
  3. Intermediate analyses - This stage encompasses all analyses performed to enable the landscape scale habitat connectivity modelling for both tits species and compute connectivity metrics using the Graphab software (FoltÃªte et al., 2021). Through this stage, the final dataset is generated (ndata_complete; i.e.Â the clean exploitable dataset completed with connectivity metrics). This stage is described in the Intermediate analyses report (the present document).
  4. Exploratory Data Analyses (EDA) - This stage describes all EDA and preliminary assumption checks made on the final dataset that are required to plan proper statistical analyses for hypotheses testing. This stage is described in the Exploratory data analyses and preparation report.
  5. Statistical analyses - This last stage includes all statistical procedures meant to test our study hypotheses, produce results and assess their reliability. This stage is described in the Statistical analyses report.

1.2.2. Content of this report

This document presents all analyses related to the third stage of our data processing methodology, that is intermediate analyses designed to model the landscape scale habitat connectivity modelling for Great tits and Blue tits in our study area.

2. Local habitat quality modelling

2.1. Rationale

In order to model the habitat connectivity of our focal species with the Graphab software (FoltÃªte et al., 2021), we first have to approximate the quality of every habitat patches (i.e.Â patch capacity), hence enabling weighting the nodes of the graph. Usually, this habitat quality is simply approximated by the patch cover area. In this study, we tried to obtained a more meaningful proxy of habitat quality for tits by developing a model predicting the birdsâ clutch size using local environmental variables only, hence the denomination of âlocal habitat quality modelsâ, one for each species.
Provided we could build reliable predictive models based on our nestbox data, the idea was to use these models to interpolate titsâ potential clutch size for all habitat pixels of our landcover map of the study area, and then evaluate the potential accuracy gained from this procedure compared to the simple use of habitat patches cover area for connectivity metrics computation.

2.2. Local habitat model for the Great tits (Parus major)

2.2.1. Model building

We built a Random Forest (RF) regression model (Breiman, 2001) using the {randomForest} package (Liaw & Wiener, 2002). We used clutch size as a response variable and, as spatial interpolation was our goal, we only considered spatially continuous variables as predictors: i.e.Â coord_x, coord_y, noise_m, noise_iq, built_area, open_area, soft_manag_area, woodyveg_volume, woodyveg_sd (for the meaning of the variables, readers are referred to table S1).

As regular RF implementations are known to have robust default hyperparameters, we did no hyperparameters tuning and thus grew a forest of 500 regression trees, each one based on a random subset of \(p/3\) predictors and \(0.632\) bootstrapped samples. Since we performed no model optimisation, we avoided the need for repeated k-fold cross validation or similar resampling procedures (Hastie et al., 2009; Harrell, 2015). The modelâs performances were evaluated using its Mean Squared Error (MSE) and the automatically computed \(R^{2}_{oob}\) (i.e.Â based on the out-of-bag samples). Additionally, we also computed the global variable importance metrics, using the permutation-based method in order to avoid the known bias associated with the Gini-based method (e.g. Strobl et al., 2007).

2.2.2. Predictive performance and stability evaluation

Our Random Forest regression model obtained a MSE of 2.224875 and explained roughly 12.5% of clutch sizeâs variance (\(R^{2}_{oob}\) = 12.43). To evaluate the stability of these outputs, I reiterated this modelling process a hundred times and monitored the variance of the \(R^{2}_{oob}\) and the variable importance metrics:

Fortunately, we can see that the \(R^{2}_{oob}\) values converges towards ~12%.

This figure shows that the variables importance is also stable across iterations. The grown forest thus seems reliable enough to be used for predictions.

2.3. Local habitat model for the Blue tits (Cyanistes caeruleus)

Despite our efforts, we could not obtain reliable results with our Blue tits data, likely because of insufficient sample size. Consequently, we will only model this species habitat connectivity using patches cover area as proxy of habitat capacity.

First, we investigated the existence of potential outliers in the metrics:

Figure M3pm. Cleveland dotplots for all computed F-metrics for Parus major nestboxes using AREA as capacity

It appears all F metrics have extreme values that may be viewed as outliers even though the situation is less pronounced when beta = 0. As expected from the graphical exploration performed on QGIS (not shown here), values of the d2 capa1 Rr metric has the nicest distribution among all Rr and Dr metrics.
Interestingly, the plots suggest that Dr metrics are not just the inverse of the Fâs.

As expected, most extreme values for F and Rr metrics are either located in the âParc de la ColombiÃ¨reâ (i.e.Â the largest urban park of the city, by far, which is also close to the riparian corridor of the Ouche river) or in the âCombe des noyersâ (i.e.Â the residential area located in the forested hillsides on the south-west of the city). Similarly, sites with Dr_capa1 values > 3500 (i.e.Â nestboxes from which tits have to move at least 3.5 km [in cost distance] in order to visit enough habitat patches to reach 5000mÂ² of cumulated woody area) are almost all located within the city centre (but not âpriv_chenoveâ).

We then looked at their histograms:

Figure M4pm. Histograms for all computed F-metrics for Parus major nestboxes using AREA as capacity

We can see that none of the metrics are close to a normal distribution. This might be problematic. Still, some have distributions that might be approximately normalised with a log or a square-root transformation.

3.1.2. Multivariate exploration

We then investigated the bivariate correlations among the connectivity metrics and some other predictors (for the sake of visualisation, not all variables are plotted):

Figure M5pm. Correlation matrix displaying Spearmanâs \(\rho\) for all computed F metrics and some selected predictors. Only significant correlations are displayed (with \(\alpha\) = 0.05)

Obviously, there are many things to say here:

  • First, most predictors are significantly correlated with each others, and all connectivity metrics are correlated with each other, suggesting that they share much of the same information. We can also see than, that patch_area displays the same correlation patterns as the connectivity metrics, but with weaker correlations.
  • Second, woody vegetation cover and volume are strongly positively correlated with all connectivity metrics (or negatively with the Drâs), which was expected but might be problematic for modelling.
  • Third, the F metrics computed with the largest distances are extremely positively correlated with each other BUT LESS SO with the other variables, perhaps because the distance is so high that the metric stops being linked to local environmental conditions. We can also see that they are negatively correlated with latitude displaying the expected North-South gradient of connectivity or woody cover (i.e.Â there are more large woody areas in the south of the city).


To further study distributions and bivariate correlations, we plotted various numeric predictor against each others. It gave us the possibility to start investigating potential multivariate outliers.

Figure M6pm. Bivariate relationship among computed F-metrics and some key explanatory variables

This figure emphasizes once more that the predictor space could have been better sampled as there clearly are some clear multivariate outliers (or, at least, extreme values).
Other interesting observations can be made:

  1. Connectivity metrics are clearly related to each other, linearly or quadratically.
  2. Interestingly, the Rr metrics (6-7th rows) do not display clear multivariate outliers!
  3. We can confirm that the connectivity increases with decreasing built and open areas!
  4. The last rows show that the sites with the highest woody volume are not necessarily those with the highest connectivity metrics : i.e.Â although rank-based correlations are extremely high (particularly for metrics with beta = 1), the plot shows clear bivariate outliers as well as rather flat relationships between these variables! It could mean that the supposedly correlated relationship between woody vegetation volume and our connectivity proxies may not be so analytically problematic and we could argue that it legitimises our hypothesis of an interaction between these two variables of interest!

So, up to this point, weâd be rather inclined into retaining the d2 and/or capa1-based connectivity metrics for modelling.

3.1.3. Y-based data exploration

To avoid illegitimate data-driven model development, we first started by dividing our dataset into training and testing sets (representing 65% and 35% of the total sample size, respectively).

Then, we looked at simple rank-based bivariate correlations:

Figure M7pm. Correlation matrix displaying Spearmanâs \(\rho\) for all computed F metrics and our response variables on our training set. Only significant correlations are displayed (with \(\alpha\) = 0.05)

On this figure, we can see that:

  1. Most response variables appear unrelated to our F metrics (according to Spearmanâs rank correlations), with the exception of clutch size that is mildly correlated with all of them. Clutch size is also negatively correlated with the woody or patch area variables!
  2. Surprisingly, the parental condition variables (that are covariates) display a very peculiar pattern with father_cond being positively correlated with our connectivity metrics while the reverse is partially true for mother_cond.

To further examine these relationships, we plotted the Great tits couplesâ clutch size and the mass of nestlings against all our computed connectivity metrics:

Figure M8a_pm. Bivariate scatterplot between Parus majorâs clutch size and each potential connectivity metric, with and without log-tranformation

We can see that log-transformations could indeed be useful.
To deepen our grasp of the metrics relevance, we also looked at the relationships with the mass of nestlings:

Figure M8b_pm. Bivariate scatterplot between the mass of Parus major nestlings and each potential connectivity metric, with and without log-tranformation

Same comment as for clutch_size.


3.1.4. Conclusion

Overall, these observations support our initial preference for the d2-based connectivity metrics.

We then looked at their histograms:

Figure M4cc. Histograms for all computed F-metrics for Cyanistes caeruleus nestboxes using AREA as capacity

Most metrics are not close to a normal distribution. This might be problematic.

3.2.2. Multivariate exploration

We then investigated the bivariate correlations among the connectivity metrics and some other predictors:

Figure M5cc. Correlation matrix displaying Spearmanâs \(\rho\) for all computed F metrics and some selected predictors. Only significant correlations are displayed (with \(\alpha\) = 0.05)

Obviously, patterns are quite similar to those observed for Parus major:

  • First, most predictors are significantly correlated with each others, and most F or Rr metrics are positively correlated with each other, suggesting that they may carry pretty much the same information.
  • Second, woody vegetation cover and volume are strongly correlated with all connectivity metrics.


To further study distributions and bivariate correlations, we plotted various numeric predictor against each others. It gave us the possibility to start investigating potential multivariate outliers.

Figure M6cc. Bivariate relationship among computed connectivity metrics and some key explanatory variables

This figure shows patterns relatively similar with those observed for Parus major, but values are sometimes more extreme.

3.2.3. Y-based data exploration

To avoid illegitimate data-driven model development, we first started by dividing our dataset into training and testing sets (representing 65% and 35% of the total sample size, respectively).

Then, we looked at simple rank-based bivariate correlations:

Figure M7cc. Correlation matrix displaying Spearmanâs \(\rho\) for all computed F metrics and our response variables on our training set. Only significant correlations are displayed (with \(\alpha\) = 0.05)

On this figure, we can see that:

  1. Unlike for Parus major, several response variables appear correlated to some connectivity metrics (according to Spearmanâs rank correlations).
  2. Similarly to PM, correlations seem negative for the reproduction related variables and positive for the morphometric one.

To further examine these relationships, we plotted the Blue tits couplesâ clutch size and the mass of nestlings against some computed metrics:

Figure M8a_cc. Bivariate scatterplot between Cyanistes caeruleusâs clutch size and each potential connectivity metric, with and without log-tranformation

Again, we can see that a log-transformation could be useful for some metrics but definitely not for all of them.

Figure M8b_cc. Bivariate scatterplot between the mass of Cyanistes caeruleus nestlings and each potential connectivity metric, with and without log-tranformation

Same observation here.

3.2.4. Conclusion

Overall, these observations converges with what we saw for Parus major and support our decision to select d2-based connectivity metrics for inferential modelling.
